**Steps to Reproduce**:

Use the following code:

````
    public record struct TypeMapCapacity
    {
        private int _Size;
        private readonly int _MaxSize;
    
        public readonly required int Size
        {
            get => _Size;
            init => _Size = value;
        }
    
        public readonly int? MaxSize
        {
            get => _MaxSize;
            init // Triggering IDE0251 even though member is readonly.
            {
                //_Size = (int)value;
                //Size = 0;
                //_Size = (int)value;
                //_Size = 0;
    
                if (value is not null)
                {
                    _MaxSize = (int)value;
    
                    //Size = (int)value;
                    //Size = 0;
                    //_Size = (int)value;
                    //_Size = 0;
                }
                else
                {
                    _MaxSize = _Size;

                    //Size = (int)value;
                    //Size = 0;
                    //_Size = (int)value;
                    //_Size = 0;
                }
    
                //Size = (int)value;
                //Size = 0;
                //_Size = (int)value;
                //_Size = 0;
            
                //FooProperty = true;
            }
        }
    
        public bool FooProperty { get; set; }
    }
````

**Behavior**:

In above code, IDE0251 triggers on `MaxSize` init accessor. Applying the suggested fix does nothing, and previewing the suggested fix shows the message **🛈 No Changes**.

Uncommenting *ANY* of the statements in the above code satisfies the analyzer.

As far as I can tell, the analyzer trips when in `init` an assignment is made to a readonly field unless, *if at any point*, a non-readonly field is either directly or indirectly assigned to, or a non-readonly property.

